tehsil\n<!-- Mandi -->\n| mark-coord2 = {{coord|33.7972|74.2551}}\n| mark2 = Red pog.svg \n| mark-size2 = 8\n| label2 = Mandi\n| label-size2 = 12 \n| label-color2 = hard red\n| label-pos2 = right |label-offset-x2 = 0 |label-offset-y2 = 0\n| mark-title2 = Mandi\n| mark-image2 =\n| mark-description2 = Mandi tehsil\n<!-- Surankote -->\n| mark-coord3 = {{coord|33.640579|74.262051}}\n| mark3 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3 = 8\n| label3 = Surankote\n| label-size3 = 12 \n| label-color3 = hard red\n| label-pos3 = top |label-offset-x3 = 0 |label-offset-y3 = 0\n| mark-title3 = Surankote\n| mark-image3 =\n| mark-description3 = Surankote tehsil\n<!-- Mendhar  -->\n| mark-coord4 = {{coord|33.604852|74.142988}}\n| mark4 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4 = 8\n| label4 = Mendhar\n| label-size4 = 12 \n| label-color4 = hard red\n| label-pos4 = right |label-offset-x4 = 0 |label-offset-y4 = 0\n| mark-title4 = Mendhar\n| mark-image4 =\n| mark-description4 = Mendhar tehsil\n<!-- Mankote -->\n| mark-coord5 = {{coord|33.594368|74.097104}}\n| mark5 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size5 = 8\n| label5 = Mankote\n| label-size5 = 12 \n| label-color5 = hard red\n| label-pos5 = left |label-offset-x5 = 0 |label-offset-y5 = 0\n| mark-title5 = Mankote\n| mark-image5 =\n| mark-description5 = Mankote tehsil\n<!-- Bala Kote -->\n| mark-coord6 = {{coord|33.501455|74.180174}}\n| mark6 = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size6 = 8\n| label6 = Bala Kote\n| label-size6 = 12\n| label-color6 = hard red\n| label-pos6 = right |label-offset-x6 = 0 |label-offset-y6 = 0\n| mark-title6 = Bala Kote\n| mark-image6=\n| mark-description6= Bala Kote tehsil\n}}\nThe District headquarters is in the [[Poonch (town)|Poonch]] city. Rahul Yadev is the current District Commissioner. Presently District Poonch in Jammu and Kashmir is divided into six [[tehsil]]s:\n*[[Haveli Tehsil]]\n*[[Mandi Tehsil]]\n*[[Mendhar Tehsil]]\n*[[Surankote Tehsil]]\n*[[Mankote Tehsil]]\n*[[Balakote Tehsil]]\n\nEach tehsil has its [[Tehsildar]], who is the administrative head. The district is further divided into eleven. blocks: Poonch, Mandi, Loran Sathra  Mendhar, Mankote Balakote, Surankote and Buffliaz.<ref>[http://jkrd.nic.in/listAllDistricts.pdf Statement showing the number of blocks in respect of 22 Districts of Jammu and Kashmir State including newly Created Districts] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910092544/http://jkrd.nic.in/listAllDistricts.pdf |date=2008-09-10 }} dated 2008-03-13, accessed 2008-08-30</ref> The administrative head of each block is the Block Development Officer (BDO). Each block consists of a number of [[panchayat]]s. Recently added One Sub Division(Surnkote), other is Mendhar. Poonch district has a total of 179 villages including [[Seri Khawaja]].\n\n==Economy==\nIn 2006 the [[Ministry of Panchayati Raj]] named Poonch one of the country's 250 [[Poverty in India|most backward districts]] (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=brgf/> It is one of the three districts in Jammu and Kashmir currently receiving funds from the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme (BRGF).<ref name=brgf>{{cite web|author=Ministry of Panchayati Raj|date=8 September 2009|title=A Note on the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme|publisher=National Institute of Rural Development|url=http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf|accessdate=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405033402/http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf|archivedate=5 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nPoonch District has 3 assembly constituencies: Surankote, Mendhar and Poonch Haveli. In 19 November 2018 assembly is dissolved by governor Satya pal Malik. The former M.L.A of Poonch Haveli is Shah Mohammed Tantray of [[Jammu & Kashmir Peoples Democratic Party]], Mohammed Akram of [[Indian National Congress]] is currently representing Surankote constituency and Mendhar is being represented by Javid Rana of [[Jammu & Kashmir National Conference]]. Poonch district comes in Jammu-Poonch Lok Sabha Constituency.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ceojammukashmir.nic.in/ERos_AERos.html | title=ERO's and AERO's | publisher=Chief Electoral Officer, Jammu and Kashmir | accessdate=2008-08-28 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022185235/http://ceojammukashmir.nic.in/eros_aeros.html | archivedate=2008-10-22 }}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Poonch district (2011)<ref>{{cite web |title=C-1 Population By Religious Community |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-01.html|publisher=Census |accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref> <!-- Click on Jammu and Kashmir -->\n|label1 = [[Islam]]\n|value1 = 90.45\n|color1 = Green\n|label2 = [[Hinduism]]\n|value2 = 6.84\n|color2 = Orange\n|label3 = [[Sikhism]]\n|value3 = 2.35\n|color3 = Yellow\n|label4 = [[Christianity]]\n|value4 = 0.20\n|color4 = Blue\n|label5 = Other\n|value5 = 0.02\n|color5 = Black\n|label6 = [[Irreligion|Atheist]]\n|value6 = 0.15\n|color6 = Grey\n}}\n\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Poonch district, India has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 476,835,{{cn|date=May 2019}} roughly equal to the nation of [[Suriname]].<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web | author = US Directorate of Intelligence | title = Country Comparison:Population | url = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2119rank.html | accessdate = 2011-10-01 | quote = \nSuriname 491,989 July 2011 est.\n}}</ref>  This gives it a ranking of 548th in India (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]). The district has a population density of {{convert| 285 |PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}}. Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001-2011 was 27.97%. Poonch has a [[sex ratio]] of 890 [[Women in India|females]] for every 1000 males, and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 68.69%.  The district is 90.45% Muslim.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\nResident ethnicities include [[Gujjar]]s, [[Bakerwal]]s, [[Jatts]] , [[Pahari people (Kashmir)|Pahari]]s, [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]]s, [[Kashmiri people|Kashmiris]] and [[Rajput]]s. Gujjars mostly reside on the slopes of mountains. The inhabitants typically cultivate small plots of land, and own some cattle. Gujjars and Bakerwals (nomadic tribes) speak [[Gojri]], apart from Kashmiris the rest of the population speak [[Pahari-Pothwari]] (Poonchi) and only a minuscule population may be speaking [[Dogri]].<ref name=\"ethno-dgo\">{{cite web|title=Dogri|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/18/language/dgo/index.html|website=Ethnologue|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Baba|first1=Yasar Muhammad|title=My land my people: Kashmir in perspective|date=2007|publisher=Gulshan Books|page=85|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X4UMAQAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\n\n{{As of|2011|the 2011 census}} the religions followed in the district were:\nIslam\t(90.45%), Hinduism (6.84%), Sikhism (2.35%), Christianity (0.20%) and small numbers of Buddhists, Jains, and others.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\n== Peace ==\nWith the recent developments between India and Pakistan, the divided people are again coming into contact with each other. The opening of the Poonch-Rawalakot bus is an important step in this direction.\n\n==Transport==\n===Air===\nThere is a small [[Poonch Airport|airstrip]] located which is mainly used by the Indian Army. \n===Rail===\nThere is no railway connectivity to Poonch yet.\n===Road===\nPoonch district is connected to the summer capital [[Jammu]] by an all-weather road. It also has road connectivity with [[Srinagar]] through the pictureresque [[Mughal Road]].  \nA bus across the LOC, the [[Poonch (town)|Poonch]]-[[Rawalakot]] bus has helped to re-establish ties across the border.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Poonch1.jpg\nImage:Poonch2.jpg\nImage:Poonch3.jpg\nImage:Poonch4.jpg\nImage:Poonch5.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[1947 Poonch Rebellion]]\n* [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]]\n* [[Poonch District, Pakistan]]\n* [[Moghul road]]\n* [[Pir Panjal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061210162225/http://poonch.nic.in/welcome.html Official website of District Poonch] \u2013 Administered by India.\n* [http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/0105_PART_B_DCHB_PUNCH.pdf 2011 District Census Handbook]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Poonch district\n|North     = [[Baramula district]]\n|Northeast = [[Badgam district]]\n|East      = \n|Southeast = [[Kulgam district]]\n|South     = [[Rajouri district]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = ''[[Kashmir conflict|Disputed region]]''\n|Northwest = \n}}\n\n{{Jammu and Kashmir topics}}\n{{Minority Concentrated Districts in India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poonch District}}\n[[Category:Districts of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Poonch district, India| ]]\n[[Category:Minority Concentrated Districts in India]]\n[[Category:Districts of India]]\n\n[[sv:Poonch]]\n", "name_user": "FlyJet777", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poonch_district,_India"}
